[Deal "N:AK98764.KQ7.K73. T3.984.A9.Q87632 QJ2.J2.QJ862.AKJ 5.AT653.T54.T954"]
[BoardVersionToken "481c500d3d21408333604badccfb00261deaac9dbc9ce7903e488bbdcea54b9a"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 3S Pass 4C Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{You have a great hand - how will you start the bidding? 
You open 1\S. South responds 2\D, a 2/1 force to game.   
You have a big hand, perhaps in the slam range, but first priority is to set a trump suit. So you contend yourself with a rebid of 2\S.  South agrees on trumps by bidding 3\S (not Fast Arrival).  What do you do now? 
Now you make your slam try by using a Control-showing cue-bid. She bids 4\C, showing first or second round control of the suit (Ace or king, or singleton or void).
South bids 4\s.  What do you do now? 

South's next bid would be a control-showing bid of her own - IF SHE HAD ONE. Since she cannot win the first or second round of either red suit she just returns to 4\S. North realizes that they are off two red Aces and passes.
Notice that North did not fall into the Blackwood trap. If you HAD asked for Aces, South would have shown one Ace and North wouldn't know what to do next. She might have figured the odds favored that one Ace being a red one and tried the slam. Moral: Don't use Blackwood when you have a void.}

